w-lying land’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’.","History: Nathaneal Eaton, born in Coventry, England, <i>c.</i> 1609, came to MA in 1637 and was the first head of Harvard College, in 1638–39."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Eton was born about 1295, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Richard Eton de Pulford and Agnes L'Engenour. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Isabella de stockton."},"et":{"abt. 1295–":"umbes 1295–Surnud","1295–Male":"1295–Surnud","1297–Male":"1297–Surnud","1303–Male":"1303–Surnud","1310–Female":"1310–Surnud","1326–Female":"1326–Surnud","1328–1381":"1328–1381","1335–Male":"1335–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","abt. 1328":"umbes 1328","1326":"1326","1303":"1303","abt 1326":"umbes 1326","1335":"1335","1310":"1310","1297":"1297","ABT 1335":"umbes 1335","1295":"1295","1381":"1381","abt. 1295":"umbes 1295","1328":"1328","Eton, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Eaton, Cheshire, England":"Eaton, Cheshire, E